flowRoot.flowPara: Knit Grid: An Android Application for Tracking Knitting Patterns

Android is a mobile operating system created by Google that allows developers to write apps in Java. Many different kinds of devices run Android, including smartphones, tablets, wearables, and even televisions.
Android Studio is an IDE provided by Google that allows developers to write and refactor code, run an Android emulator, and debug applications with ease.

With the ever-growing prevalence or smartphones and other mobile devices, Android developers are in high demand. The students in this mobile development class will leave it well-equipped to take on internships and jobs in Android development.

These final projects are excellent portfolio pieces that demonstrate knowledge not just with Android, but with the various peripheral technologies that are key to building interesting and robust apps.
Knitting lace involves repeating a small pattern of stitches over and over again.

Some websites that sell patterns have apps for viewing those patterns, but no app exists to let a knitter create their own patterns and view them. It is also important to be able to track progress through the pattern, to make it easy to come back later.
Our app allows the user to create and view patterns, visually track progress, and upload patterns to the web to share with other knitters.

Version control: We decided to use GitHub, a website for code collaboration, to facilitate the development process. Once one of us completed a ticket, a discussion about the code was opened up in a pull request. Other developers in the project review the code and leave feedback before merging the work into the main code base.
Local database: For saving data locally, we used a library called SugarORM, which allows us to use Java objects to model our database tables.

Web component: Our web component is written using the Ruby programming language, along with the Grape API framework, to quickly build a backend server that our app can communicate with. We deployed our API on Heroku, a cloud-based application platform.
